    value: 고려시대 같은 해 같은 과거 시험에 함께 급제한 사람을 말하는데, 동년당(同年黨)ㆍ동년방(同年榜)이라고도 하였다
  - key: '[주-D002] 어질다. 회(回)여 : '
    value: 회(回)는 옛날 중국 공자(孔子)의 수제자 안자(顔子)의 이름인데, 공자는 안회(顔回)가 나이 젊으면서도 공부가 성숙한 것을 사랑하여 “어질다 회여.” 하며 칭찬하였다는 기록이 《논어(論語)》에 전한다. 여기서는 임금이, 나이가 아직 적으면서도 인격이 숙성한 윤공을 칭찬하면서, 공자가 안자를 칭찬한 이 말을 그대로 인용한 것이다.
english:
  title: Record of the Shrine at the Tomb of the Yun Family
  author: Baek Munbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yun Gong of Yuljeong was my fellow graduate. His grandson, Sojong, came to tell me: "My grandfather retired to Geumju and built a hermitage beside his mother's tomb, where he performed seasonal sacrifices. One day, returning to his hermitage after bidding farewell to his descendants, he fell ill and passed away. He was buried south of his mother's tomb. The portrait His Majesty graciously painted with his own brush now rests in that hermitage, guarded by attendants. Should we continue the seasonal offerings following his mother's practice?"

    I replied: "Hermitages at tombs are ancient practice. Long ago, Lin Chan was granted a hermitage by his mother's tomb, and people called it the Lin house at the palace gate. Though visiting tombs for sacrifices is not ancient custom, where filial piety dwells, the world cannot call it wrong. Thus the great scholars of recent times have long performed tomb sacrifices. Moreover, how could one not rebuild the hall of one's forebears? The ancients buried the body and called back the spirit, placing wooden tablets in temples. Later generations created portrait halls. The sage Cheng said: 'Among all people under heaven, if even a single hair or whisker differs from my parent, it becomes another person.' Yet from Han and Tang onward, all have esteemed portraits. How much more so when the imperial brush is incomparable, with the spirit captured in every brushstroke? At a glance, the divine radiance seems alive—who has time to count each hair? The Ritual of Sacrifice says: 'Seen in the broth, seen in the wall.' How much more when the likeness is exact and comes from the imperial hand? The Rites prescribe that scholars establish temples for two generations, and great officials for three. When ritual accords with antiquity, it must adapt to the present. To place a temple at the tomb and a portrait in the temple may not accord with the ancient way, yet the hermitage is the ancestor's bequest and cannot be abandoned; the portrait is an imperial gift and cannot be treated lightly. Would it not be better to make the hermitage serve as the temple and the portrait as the spiritual tablet, so that posterity understands that the father's way is not to be altered, and that the imperial grace is honored? Is this not the art of balancing ritual law with human feeling, drawing from antiquity to illuminate the present? Moreover, our people are constrained by foreign teachings, and both temples and sacrifices have fallen into disuse. Could there be a better way to establish a shrine at the tomb, preserving the eternal law while adapting to circumstances, strengthening the weak and inspiring virtue?

    Yun Gong's virtue and office are fully recorded in his official biography, and the historians have given him special mention, so I need not elaborate here. Yet Gong possessed great capacity. In his youth, devoted to learning, he often recited the words of Fan Zhongshu: 'To worry about the world's troubles before one's own, to rejoice in the world's joys before one's own.' He believed that a true man either does not pursue worldly affairs or, if he does, how could he not do so? From then on, entering the academy and living among his fellow students, his spirit was noble and stood apart. In the year Jeongsa, he passed the National Academy examination in fourth place. In Gyeongsin, when Ikjae became director of the civil examination, Gong passed the literary examination in sixth place. Appointed as clerk at Gyeongsan, he encouraged agricultural work, repaired schools, and had the people of the region visit their ancestors' tombs, whereupon filial virtue became honored among the customs.

    Later promoted to proofreader, he entered the Hall of Worthies. In the year Imsin, when the late king resided in the Yuan capital, Gong went to serve him. The king said: 'My son does not match his elder brother. I would ask you to teach and guide him,' and bestowed wine upon him. Gong bowed and declined, saying: 'Your servant is ignorant and lowly, already in his middle years. When the crown prince reaches maturity, your servant will be in decline.' The king replied: 'To instruct in virtue and righteousness, none excel the aged and wise.' At this time Gong was forty-four. The following year, when the king returned to the east and arrived at Pyeongyang, Gong was appointed inspector of royal guards. The king, seeing Gong, often recited: 'Worthy indeed, Hui!' When an imperial envoy arrived, the king had Gong read the proclamation and bestowed upon him the purple robe of a superior instructor. Soon after, he was promoted to judge. In the year Mulin, he was appointed counselor and participated in governance. In Gimyo, he supervised the National Academy examination and selected ninety-nine candidates including An Wonryong. The king said to Gong: 'Do not forget to exert yourself for my son.' Gong replied: 'Your servant has already exhausted his humble strength in service to Your Majesty. How could it reach to future times?'

    After this, when King Myeongryung had no heir and young King Chungjeong was of tender years, the people's hopes turned toward the present king. Gong championed his enthronement. When King Chungjeong ascended, Gong was demoted to Gwangyang. At that time eleven elders submitted a memorial hoping that the crown prince would assume the throne, and in Sinmyo year, the king indeed received the mandate. Thus Gong was held in high regard and appointed director of the Secret Council. In Jimjin, he submitted a memorial on state affairs but did not receive approval. Gong then firmly declined office at age sixty-four. He was appointed governor of Kaesong and allowed to retire. He then built a pavilion south of the city beside the Yolma Pond's imperial grace pool, naming it the Leisurely Wandering Pavilion, where he passed his days in tranquil ease. Later his rank was raised to Grand Minister of State and Counselor, which he held until his death.

    Though Gong had laid down his office and dwelt at home, the king did not forget him and wished often to see him. Thus Gong frequently attended court and offered counsel without cease—urging the suppression of apocryphal prognostications and the cessation of military campaigns, petitioning for imperial lectures on the Extended Meaning. Together with Choi Ryeong, he submitted a memorial saying: 'We beseech Your Majesty to devote perfect sincerity to the ancestral shrine, perfect filial devotion to the queen mother, frequently receive visits from elders, and ever follow the ancient protocols.' Since Gong had received the late king's dying charge, he spoke freely without reserve, not wishing to be constrained by taboos. Though the king could not always act upon his words, he treated him with great respect, always addressing him as 'Elder' without using his name.

    One day Gong told the king: 'If benevolence without resolution leads to endless procrastination, it will surely harm governance, and later remedy will come too late.' The king's countenance darkened, but soon he raised a cup and offered wine to Gong. The attending minister Hong Yeonbok, upon leaving, sighed and said: 'I did not know Yun Gong possessed such forthright courage. We cannot match him.' The king himself painted Gong's portrait and wrote above it in large characters 'Yuljeong,' then presented it to him. The great masters including Ikjae all composed poems in praise.

    Gong's grandfather, Yun Hae, served under King Gyeongryung, holding office in the Ministry of Justice and the Censorate. Going to the provinces, he served as inspector of three regions—Yangguang, Gyeongsang, and Hwaeyang—and as surveillance commissioner of Jeolla. There he settled judicial cases with wisdom and clarity. Returning to the capital, he became censor and eventually great administrator, then retired. He was known for his spotless integrity, though his household fell into poverty. He had a son named Su-pyeong who died young. He then married the lady Kim of Jinrye District and fathered Gong, named Tae.

    At nine years old, Gong recited the Classics. The imperial secretary Choi Sarib, upon seeing him, said: 'A prodigy!' and composed the "Song of the Divine Steed" for him. The great administrator wept and told Gong: 'With you alive, Su-pyeong does not truly die. You shall restore our house.' Indeed, it came to pass. With good beginning and good end, his descendants flourished abundantly.

    I once composed an essay on Yuljeong, saying: 'The chestnut grows with great difficulty, yet once grown, reaches maturity with ease. Its flowers bloom very late, yet once bloomed, flourish abundantly. Its fruit sets very late, yet once set, is harvested with ease. In its nature dwells the principle that fullness yields to emptiness and humility receives increase. Gong's rise and flourishing was the chestnut's growth; the chestnut's gathering and storing was Gong's tranquil cultivation—thus I speak of his life's beginning and end.'

    Gong once told his descendants: 'Our forebears rose from humble circumstances and transmitted the family through integrity. I lost my father young and received no proper instruction. Without virtue or talent, I was fortunate to receive the sovereign's grace, yet could repay not a hair's worth. You must be diligent, frugal, and loyal if you would preserve the family name.' Throughout his life, Gong wore hempen robes and tattered garments. Often his meals were meager, yet he remained unmoved. Each spring and autumn, when fine days arrived, he would prepare wine and feast, gathering his students and fellow graduates to receive Ikjae and other venerable ministers, where they drank, composed poetry, and rejoiced together to their hearts' content.

    In his later years, he requested retirement and returned to Gimju, settling in Imcheon. Seven years later, in the year Gyeongseul, on the seventh day of the ninth month, he passed away. Word of his death reached the court, and he was granted the posthumous name Munjeong. His tomb-side hermitage was thereafter established as a shrine.

    Sojong came to the capital and requested that I write this record for the shrine. Since I knew Gong longest and a tomb-shrine cannot exist without proper documentation, I have set this essay at the beginning. Alas! Though Ikjae supervised the examinations in his youth, he lived to eighty-two before passing into the other world, leaving but two or three students alive. Gong and Gwigok were posted to the provinces, so I alone grasped the funeral rope and wept. Three years later, Gong too passed away at eighty-two. I am now sixty-eight. As I unfold this paper and lift my brush to record Gong's virtues and deeds, I find myself bewildered, knowing not what to write.

    Gong was married four times: to the lady Mun, the lady Lee, and the lady Ki—the first Ki predeceased him, then he married another of the Ki family. All bore him sons and daughters. Gwisaeng was born of Lady Mun. Bongsaeng was born of a later wife but died early, leaving four children; a daughter married the courtier Heo Sik but predeceased him, leaving one son—all born of Lady Lee. Dongmyeong was born of Lady Ki, passed the examination in Jeongyu, and rose to vice minister of rites. A daughter married General Pak Gweryeong. The daughter of his later wife, Lady Ki, married the scholar Yi Jonjung but predeceased him, leaving two daughters. In all, Gong had nine grandsons, of whom Sojong was one, who placed first in the examination of Eulsa and served as vice minister of rites. He had four granddaughters, two grandsons by marriage, four great-grandsons, and two others of secondary descent.

    I say: Long may he be honored. Gather at his shrine and make offerings; let not this record be forgotten.
  footnotes:
    - Yuljeong (Chestnut Pavilion) was the name of the hermitage Yun Gong built in retirement, and the name by which he came to be known.
    - Fan Zhongshu (范仲淹, 989-1052), Song Dynasty statesman and philosopher, was famous for his moral idealism and these opening lines of his work are celebrated throughout East Asia.
    - Hui refers to Yan Hui (顏回), Confucius's most beloved and virtuous disciple. The king's use of this reference to praise the young Yun Gong elevates him as a model of moral excellence despite his youth.
    - The portrait painted by the king himself became an imperial treasure and was treated as a sacred object worthy of veneration in the shrine.
    - The Ritual of Sacrifice (祭義) is a classical Confucian text describing proper ritual practices; the quoted lines suggest the presence of ancestral spirits in offerings.
